courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon successful completion of the course, students will be able to
1. explain the operation of basic components of a digital circuit;
2. explain how digital computers operate at the most basic level;
3. carry out experiments on assembling and testing basic digital circuits;
4. describe the architecture of a basic computer processor;
5. design medium-complexity digital systems;
6. interpret the description of a digital system using high-level languages
7. explain safety rules and describe some common health and safety problems in laboratory.

Upon successful completion of the course, students will be able to:
1. apply mathematical methods to explain and analyze electromagnetic field and wave propagation problems;
2. explain the working principles of common microwave and optical transmission lines and devices;
3. design a simple antenna and a matching network, and conduct relevant measurement using a vector network analyzer;
4. describe key practical issues and technical challenges in radio and optical communication systems.

Upon successful completion of the course, students will be able to
1. give mathematical description of antennas and radio propagation;
2. design practical antennas for wireless terminals using industry-standard EDA software;
3. explain the basic concepts of antenna arrays;
4. explain the basic concepts of radio propagation;
5. calculate a system link budget for a given radio channel and a communication system;
6. describe the architecture of a satellite communication system.

Upon successful completion of the course, students will be able to
1. explain the roles of hardware and software in an embedded computing system;
2. explain the architecture of a modern micro-controller unit;
3. perform computer programming to control the operation of a micro-controller unit;
4. perform experiments on microcontroller hardware and software;
5. design and implement an embedded system using micro-controller unit.

Upon successful completion of the course, students will be able to
1. demonstrate an understanding of power converters used in modern electronic devices;
2. describe the performance metrics of power converter circuits;
3. analyse the performance of power converter circuits: steady-state and dynamic;
4. design power converter circuits to optimize both steady-state and dynamic performances
5. design and verify power converter circuits using a design automation tool

Upon successful completion of the course, students will be able to
1. understand and explain fundamental concepts in optics；
2. explain the principles of optical waveguides, thin film filters, optical interferometers;
3. explain the basic principles of Optical Coherence Tomography and LIDAR;
4. design micro-optical subsystems.

courses.recommended_readings:
1. Sherman Karp and Larry B. Stotts, Fundamentals of Electro-Optic Systems Design: Communications, Lidar, and Imaging, Cambridge University Press, 2013;
2. Toru Yoshizawa, Handbook of Optical Metrology: Principles and Applications, 2nd Edition, CRC Press, 2015.3. Optics (4th edition) Eugene Hecht (Addison Wesley, 2002)
3. Chih-Lin Chen, Foundations for Guided Wave Optics, Wiley Interscience, 2007

courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon successful completion of the course, students will be able to
1. Understand and explain the ideas of signal processing methods at an advanced level;
2. Appreciate how such signal processing methods are operated as tools;
3. Apply signal processing techniques to real-world problems

courses.course_syllabus:
Discrete-time signals and systems, sampling; Short-time Fourier transform;
Time-frequency analysis; Audio and speech signal processing; Digital filter design;
Spectral estimation; Optimal filters; Principal component analysis.

courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon successful completion of the course, students will be able to
1. Understand and explain the basic concepts and theory of digital image processing methods;
2. Appreciate how such digital image processing methods are applied as tools in real-world applications and systems;
3. Apply digital image processing techniques to deal with practical problems

courses.feedback_evaluation:
We welcome students’ comments and feedback on the course. There are four main channels for collecting students’ feedback.
1. Mid-term course evaluation: An informal evaluation questionnaire conducted at the mid-term of this course covers the following areas:
a) Course organization and objectives;
b) Understanding fundamental contents;
c) Pace of teaching;
d) Method of lecture delivery;
e) Overall satisfaction.
2. Informal online contact: Students can send their comments via email to the course instructor, and the course instructor will follow up.
3. Individual consulting: Students are welcome to visit the course instructor during office hours. They can exchange opinions to make the course better suits the students’ needs.
4. Faculty course questionnaire: At the end of the course, students are required to provide feedback on different aspects related to teaching and learning of the course through a formal evaluation questionnaire.

courses.learning_outcomes:
At the end of the course of studies, a student should be able to

1. Have a good understanding and appreciate the characteristics of an Electronic Engineering work environment, including employer expectation, management structure of a team, industrial standards and practices, trends and common issues in the Electronic Engineering, etc.;

2. Carry out basic duties in an Electronic Engineering work environment;

3. Exhibit good etiquette in the workplace;

4. Work independently as well as in a team environment; and

5. Communicate effectively and efficiently with peers, supervisors and possibly also clients.
